m and prefrontal cortex in older adults during incentive processing we used event related functional magnetic resonance imaging to determine whether younger and older adults differed in both self reported and neural responsiveness to anticipated monetary gains and losses the present study provides evidence for intact striatal and insular activation during gain anticipation with age but shows a relative reduction in activation during loss anticipation these findings suggest that there is an asymmetry in the procession of gains and losses in older adults that may have implications for decision making download pdf+ complete modified february 2009 pdf nat neuroscience_knutson pdf 653.6 kb parent research center on advancing decision making in aging cadma program center on the demography and economics of health and aging cdeha chpintl program topics aging search chp search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest individual differences in insular sensitvity during loss anticipation predict avoidance learning gregory r samanez larkin nick g hollon laura l carstensen brian knutson psychol sci vol 19 4 2008 pdf+ individual differences in insular sensitivity during loss anticipation predict avoidance learning samanez larkin gr hollon ng carstensen ll knutson b psychol sci vol 19 4 2008 html+ simple counts of adl dependencies do not adequately reflect older adults preferences toward states of functional impairment tamara l sims holmes th dena m bravata alan m garber lorene nelson mary k goldstein journal of clinical epidemiology vol 61 12 2008 html+ cost effectiveness of the pneumococcal vaccine in healthy younger adults pv pepper douglas k owens medical decision making vol 22 suppl 5 2002 cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 736 0815 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
